{"id":"1305.3760","submitter":"Tzay-ming Hong","authors":"Ming-Han Chou, Wei-Chao Shen, Yi-Ping Wang, Sun-Hsin Hung, and\n  Tzay-Ming Hong","title":"Qi-Wa, a problem that has plagued Chinese scrolls for millenniums","comments":"5 pages and 5 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Lett. 112, 034302 (2014)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevLett.112.034302","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.soft physics.pop-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Qi-Wa refers to the up curl on the lengths of handscrolls and hanging\nscrolls, which has troubled Chinese artisans and emperors for as long as the\nart of painting and calligraphy exists. This warp is unwelcomed not only for\naesthetic reasons, but its potential damage to the fiber and ink. Although it\nis generally treated as a part of the cockling and curling due to climate,\nmounting procedures, and conservation conditions, we emphasize that the\nintrinsic curvature incurred from the storage is in fact the main cause of\nQi-Wa. The Qi-Wa height is determined by experiments to obey scaling relations\nwith the length, width, curvature, and thickness of the scroll, which are\nsupported by Molecular Dynamics Simulation and theoretic derivations. This\nunderstanding helps us come up with plausible remedies to mitigate Qi-Wa. All\nproposals are tested on real mounted paper and in simulations. Due to the\ngeneral nature of this warp, we believe the lessons learnt from studying\nancient Chinese scrolls can be applied to modern technologies such as the\ndevelopment of flexible electronic paper and computer screen.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 16 May 2013 11:20:24 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 25 Aug 2013 12:05:33 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-01-29"}
